# Rust Patterns

## Error Handling
- Return `Result<T, E>` with typed errors via `thiserror`
- Production code: no `.unwrap()`, `.expect()`, `panic!()`
- Test code: gate with `#[expect(clippy::unwrap_used, reason = "...")]`
- Use `?` operator for propagation

## Zero-Copy
- Identifiers (`BraidId`, `Did`, `ContentHash`) use `Arc<str>` — clone is O(1)
- Use `Cow<'_, str>` at API boundaries accepting both owned and borrowed
- Use `bytes::Bytes` for zero-copy byte buffers in IPC
- Avoid `.to_string()` when `.clone()` on `Arc<str>` suffices

## async-trait
- `async-trait` crate is used for trait-object dispatch (`dyn BraidStore`, etc.)
- Native RPITIT is not object-safe; this is the correct Rust 2024 pattern
- Do NOT remove `async-trait` from traits used with `dyn` dispatch

## Module Structure
- `mod.rs` + `tests.rs` pattern for modules with tests
- `#[cfg(test)] mod tests;` at bottom of module files
- `#[cfg(any(test, feature = "test"))]` for mock implementations
- SPDX header + copyright + `//!` doc comment at top of every file
